Unlike the 9300 series, the MS390 appears to have been left behind on ROMMON version 17.5.8r. Normally, this would be upgraded as part of the IOS-XE install process on standard switches. It seems the binaries for the MS390 explicilty omits this in current versions. I belive this is because it is largly identical to the 9300 ROMMON, and later versions have introduced a simple variable to convert from Meraki mode to Catalyst mode. 

The variable is defined as BOOT_DEVICE_MODE=catalyst or BOOT_DEVICE_MODE=Meraki on 9300 switches, and can be changed using the set command once in ROMMON. Entering ROMMON on version 17.15 of the bootloader can be achieved by pressing CTRL+C on bootup when prompted. This can allow you to conert your own 9300 back to Catalyst mode on your own without Meraki support. However, this variable does not appear to work on the older version present on the MS390. I have tried setting many variable to get this to work on the MS390.

Some other very important and functional variable are present in this release. The first is SWITCH_IGNORE_STARTUP_CFG=1. On standard 9300 switches, this would be used as part of a password reset procedure. It tells the switch to ignore any and all config files present in the NVRAM and boot up fresh. Another is CONFIG_FILE=. This one is used to define where the startup-config is stored. If set to CONFIG_FILE=flash:9300-conf, the switch will now save and load it's config from flash:9300-conf. When using the wr mem or equivalent command, this is where it is being save to. A third one that's usefull for continuous troubleshooting is the MANUAL_BOOT= flag. If set to yes, it will automatically drop to ROMMON no mater what without needing to break upon startup. You can then run the boot command to proceed.
